Figures from the holiday home specialist and currency provider, Caxton FX, have revealed that demand for ski holidays is climbing high, reporting that the volume of currency purchased for ski-related trips is up 59 per cent on last year.

'British skiers are opting for the more affordable eurozone resorts, over the US and Switzerland, with the number of US dollars purchased for ski this year down on 2013,' said James Hickman, managing director of Caxton FX.

Figures for US Dollars are reportedly down 73 per cent on last year and the number of Swiss Francs bought this year is down 58 per cent since 2012.

'In contrast, the volume of Euros purchased for ski-related trips is up 64 per cent, year on year. Brits really are making the most of being closer to home where the pound has significantly strengthened against the Euro, adds Mr Hickman.' 

